description.et:
10:15-12:00 (2 hours)

-	importance of human communication in business and professional contexts and its contribution to attaining organizational and professional goals;
-	role-taking in communications (sending and receiving messages, giving feedback, job-specific roles);
-	main communication channels (written, spoken (live and online), visual (live and online);
-	interaction model of communication (sender / receiver / channel / noise / encoder / decoder / feedback);
-	communication context: organizational and national culture, time, occasion, goals;
-	communication apprehension;
-	communication ethics (personal vs organizational values, integrity, aggression, plagiarism, etc.).

10:15-12:00 (2 hours)

-	what is persuasion and how to do it effectively and ethically (no pressure, coercion or manipulation);
-	non-verbal communications: gestures, body language, proximity, movement;
-	how type of reasoning (deductive / inductive influences persuasion) influences persuasion;
-	what is interpretation and how it affects what's being heard from what's being said;
-	setting goals for speaking in front of the group;
-	audience analysis: needs, interests, 'pains';
-	structuring one's speech: selecting and organizing content, rehearsal delivery;
-	interacting with the audience during and after speaking (maintaining engagement, Q&A, etc.).

I group: 10:15-12:00 (2 hours)
II group: 12:15-14:00 (2 hours)

-	every student records an up-to-5-minute speech on the selected topic and sends it to the course teacher - to jointly analyze during the colloquium;
-	speeches are played in the audience and analyzed: using the learned material, students comment on the goals, structure, consideration of the audience's needs, etc.;
-	a course teacher contributes to the analysis of speeches after the students have expressed their structured opinions on their fellow's speeches;
-	personal speaking-related recommendations are given to every student, in line with the course material.

III group (ONLINE): 10:15-12:00

-	every student records an up-to-5-minute speech on the selected topic and sends it to the course teacher - to jointly analyze during the colloquium;
-	speeches are played in the audience and analyzed: using the learned material, students comment on the goals, structure, consideration of the audience's needs, etc.;
-	a course teacher contributes to the analysis of speeches after the students have expressed their structed opinions on their fellow's speeches;
-	personal speaking-related recommendations are given to every student, in line with the course material.

1. part: 10:15-12:00 (2 hours)
2. part: 12:15-14:00 (2 hours), Guest Speaker - Annika Ploom, Chief HR Officer, Foxway

-	why write motivation letters?
-	goals and formats of resumes (what’s a video-resume and how it works);
- LinkedIn profile structure and optimal content;
-	‘targeting’ employer’s needs and showcasing your strengths through a resume;
-	how to describe one’s useful skills when one has no prior work experience;
-	how resumes and motivation letters are interpreted by the prospective employers;
-	job interview specifics – employer expectation, candidate self-presentation, etc.

I group: 10:15-12:00 (2 hours)
II group: 12:15-14:00 (2 hours)

-	answering questions regarding resume & motivation letter / LinkedIn profile content;
-	discussing frequently made mistakes;
-	showcasing (anonymized) good solutions used in students’ LinkedIn profiles, resumes and motivation letters;
-	troubleshooting on (anonymized) mistakes / phrases that could be improved from students’ resumes, motivation letters, LinkedIn profiles.

10:15-12:00 (2 hours)

-	active listening - how to listen productively;
-	feedback giving and receiving: types of feedback (evaluational / developmental), formats and approaches to giving feedback, key mistakes and 'no-no's' of feedback giving and receiving;
-	conducting business meetings
-	how organizational and corporate culture affect workplace communications - types of national cultures and how they influence approach to and content of communications (additional reading).

all students attend, 12:15-14:00 (2 hours)

-	resolving a workplace situation involving the need to give, receive and process feedback in a multi-cultural team;
-	students work in class in groups to come up with solutions and present them.

part I: 10:15-12:00 (2 hours)
part II: 12:15-14:00 (2 hours)

-	students prepare for the meeting simulation in groups of 5;
-	using the learned course material about messages, persuasion, feedback, reasoning (deductive / inductive), and public speaking, students are to 'conduct' a business meeting aiming to attain the goals in the context, outlined in the template;
feedback regarding the meetings is given in class, after every simulation, first by fellow students, then - by course teacher

III group (ONLINE): 14.00-15.45

-	students prepare for the meeting simulation in groups of 5;
-	using the learned course material about messages, persuasion, feedback, reasoning (deductive / inductive), and public speaking, students are to 'conduct' a business meeting aiming to attain the goals in the context, outlined in the template;
feedback regarding the meetings is given in class, after every simulation, first by fellow students, then - by course teacher
